WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.360
Okay. Hello everyone. Today, I will talk about the use of GitHub Copilot in R Shiny Development.

00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:10.960
Now, raise your hand if you think this is a shiny app.

00:00:12.200 --> 00:00:17.639
Raise your hand if you think this is a shiny app. Well, this is. I see your hands. Okay. This is a shiny app.

00:00:17.639 --> 00:00:24.559
This is a very ugly shiny app. It looks like the first ugly shiny app that we probably have created 5-10 years ago.

00:00:24.559 --> 00:00:30.799
It's a very simple app. It allows the user to pick a few tech stocks and see the recent price changes.

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:36.160
Now, how about this one? Raise your hand if you think this is also a shiny app.

00:00:37.880 --> 00:00:45.240
Okay. I see fewer hands. This is actually a shiny app, but you are correct because this was not a shiny app.

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:53.799
It was initially created using another front-end framework, JCode, but then I used Copilot to convert it to a shiny UI.

00:00:53.799 --> 00:01:00.840
And this is a very interesting use case here because oftentimes, if your organization has an online presence

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:06.519
that was created using another front-end framework, but as an asset data analyst or data developer,

00:01:06.519 --> 00:01:13.639
you want to create a shiny app that looks like it without spending too much time with CSS or HTML,

00:01:13.639 --> 00:01:15.680
actually Copilot can be a lot of help.

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:27.279
Now, today I want to convince you that if you are a data professional with a background in analytics or statistics,

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:35.559
if you want to try out Copilot, then Rshiny is a great place for you to start.

00:01:35.559 --> 00:01:43.879
And if you, like many of us in this room, have already been playing around with Copilot and R, I want to share my tips and tricks with you.

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:52.800
Why? Because the R language, the R programming language is unique in that it is predominantly used for data analytics purposes.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:02:02.160
And according to a survey, 75% of all R users use it for analytics purposes and half of them use it for educational purposes.

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:07.080
This means the front-end, the web app is essential for us.

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:13.199
It's critical for us to communicate our data and our findings to our students, our clients, our stakeholders.

00:02:13.199 --> 00:02:20.199
But it is typically, in often cases, it's not where our specialty is.

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:30.080
By using Copilot, we'll be able to automate a lot of things on the front-end, automate a lot of things that are routine, tedious, for example, tests or documentation,

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:37.479
and focus our time and energy on where our value added is, which is data analytics and statistics.

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:45.360
And to borrow the term used by Melissa yesterday, if you are Gen AI fearful or Gen AI skeptical, listen to my talk.

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:49.199
I want to convince you to try out Copilot for Rshine.

00:02:49.199 --> 00:02:55.119
Now, before diving into the details of Copilot, just quickly go through.

00:02:55.119 --> 00:03:03.360
Copilot was collaboratively developed by OpenAI, GitHub, and Microsoft, and it shares the base GPT model.

00:03:03.399 --> 00:03:07.800
But it was specifically trained to provide code as a response.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:12.880
And throughout the session, we will see the superpower of large language models.

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:17.960
But keep in mind, it was trained to provide the code as a response.

00:03:17.960 --> 00:03:23.279
Now, it is supported by the most widely used R IDE, which is RStudio.

00:03:23.279 --> 00:03:29.199
And if you are interested in trying out this positron, also with Copilot, it's not currently supported.

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:35.880
But there are a lot of alternative online or local LAMs that have extensions for positron.

00:03:35.880 --> 00:03:40.960
And if you still want to stick with Copilot, you can use the chat R package as an alternative.

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:49.639
So chat R package provides this interactive interface between the R user and large language models through the IDE.

00:03:49.639 --> 00:03:56.160
Now, I divide the basic workflow of using Copilot in Rshiny into four parts.

00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:59.279
Prompt, response, context, and iteration.

00:03:59.279 --> 00:04:01.240
I will go through them now.

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:04.360
The first part is a prompt response workflow.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:05.800
So what's a prompt?

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:09.600
We have all the great prompts given by Melissa, given by Joe.

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:18.679
And a prompt is something that we write either in human language or in code with a direct purpose for Copilot to provide a response.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:26.559
Now, according to Microsoft, there are three principles of writing effective prompts, single, short, and specific.

00:04:26.559 --> 00:04:35.160
And in the context of using Copilot for Rshiny, three types of prompts that I find the most useful and I want to share with you now,

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:38.119
command type, question type, and the leading type.

00:04:38.119 --> 00:04:40.279
And here on the screen, you see the command type.

00:04:40.279 --> 00:04:41.679
It's very straightforward.

00:04:41.679 --> 00:04:44.200
It tells Copilot what to do.

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:54.880
So in this case, I want to create, I want to use Copilot to create the UI for this very simple stock price app.

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:59.480
And I divide this task into three single steps.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:03.519
The overall UI, the visualizations, and the user input.

00:05:03.519 --> 00:05:05.720
And each sentence is short.

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:07.679
Now, what do I mean by specific?

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:13.160
So specific means you tell Copilot not only what to do, but also how to do,

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:18.959
because there are oftentimes more than one thing, more than one way to do a thing in Rshiny,

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:24.519
and especially when the specifications are not in very detail.

00:05:24.519 --> 00:05:32.399
Okay, so suppose I'm not sure how to create the user input, the part that let the user select the stock ticker.

00:05:32.399 --> 00:05:34.519
What do I do to be more specific?

00:05:34.519 --> 00:05:36.480
Well, I can ask Copilot.

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:39.799
So there's a second type of prompt, the question type.

00:05:39.799 --> 00:05:44.600
Remember, Copilot was created to provide code as a response.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:49.399
Therefore, if you want to see human language response, you need to be very specific.

00:05:49.399 --> 00:05:53.200
You tell Copilot answering English instead of code.

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:59.040
And the second type of prompt, the question, and then I ask my question.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:02.079
And I'm also using the third type of prompt here, lead in.

00:06:02.079 --> 00:06:03.359
So what's lead in?

00:06:03.399 --> 00:06:10.720
You are leading in Copilot to provide the response you want to see by starting with the first few letters

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:14.079
or the first few words that you want Copilot to provide.

00:06:14.079 --> 00:06:20.320
So in this case, I type answer to make sure Copilot knows it needs to give an answer in human language

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:23.079
instead of continuing to write your question.

00:06:23.079 --> 00:06:27.720
So if you don't do this, oftentimes Copilot will continue to write your question.

00:06:27.720 --> 00:06:32.160
And as we can see, Copilot's great at telling us the very basic function,

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:35.279
very basic package that we can use in this case.

00:06:35.279 --> 00:06:37.440
All right, the next part, context.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:43.279
So context is different from prompt in that it's typically not something we specifically create

00:06:43.279 --> 00:06:46.200
to let Copilot have a response.

00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:49.079
Most likely, it's something that you already have.

00:06:49.079 --> 00:06:53.519
And the most important source of context is a code in your code base.

00:06:53.519 --> 00:06:59.799
So here, I'm using the example of asking Copilot to create this UI.

00:06:59.799 --> 00:07:08.559
So I want Copilot to convert the front end of my personal blog from HTML, JQL, to R Shiny.

00:07:08.559 --> 00:07:13.040
Now, the most important context in this case is the index.html file,

00:07:13.040 --> 00:07:16.359
which is where the web page comes from.

00:07:16.359 --> 00:07:20.079
And there are other files in the code base as well.

00:07:20.119 --> 00:07:22.119
Now, oh, sorry.

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:30.959
Okay, Copilot attaches different levels of importance to the context in your code base.

00:07:30.959 --> 00:07:34.920
And the most important context should be in the current active tab.

00:07:34.920 --> 00:07:39.559
So make sure that you open the current active tab, which is the index file.

00:07:39.559 --> 00:07:45.559
The other open tabs in your IDE, in this case, the CSS file, the JS file,

00:07:45.559 --> 00:07:47.920
they are referred to by the HTML file.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:51.200
So they are also important, open them in the IDE.

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:55.720
And when you initially set up Copilot for your R Studio,

00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:58.119
you have the option to index project file.

00:07:58.119 --> 00:07:59.440
What does that mean?

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:08.239
It means you provide all the files, all the code in your project as a context for Copilot to use.

00:08:08.239 --> 00:08:15.200
Now, when I set, when I put the most important context in the currently open tab,

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:17.279
I point to the context, right?

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:19.799
I tell Copilot, okay, what it is.

00:08:19.799 --> 00:08:23.640
And then also I tell Copilot why it is important.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:28.679
So in this case, I want to create R code that comes from this HTML.

00:08:28.679 --> 00:08:32.960
I actually do not create, I do not start with an R script first

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:37.520
because I want to stay in the same file as the most important context.

00:08:37.520 --> 00:08:43.520
So I actually ask Copilot to create the R code inside the HTML file.

00:08:43.559 --> 00:08:47.400
And when the suggestions are complete, when the code is complete,

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:51.479
I then copy and paste the code to an R script.

00:08:51.479 --> 00:08:56.119
And this is a very useful use pattern in this case.

00:08:56.119 --> 00:09:00.760
Now, the second source of context is knowledge on the internet.

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:07.280
So in this case, the important knowledge is in this specific documentation.

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:11.080
And the power of large language models we see

00:09:11.080 --> 00:09:14.760
is that we don't do copy and paste anything from the internet.

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:18.679
We just need to provide the URL and under the hood,

00:09:18.679 --> 00:09:23.760
the large language models have already associated with the URL,

00:09:23.760 --> 00:09:27.159
with the actual text in that webpage.

00:09:27.159 --> 00:09:31.119
And I then tell Copilot why this is important.

00:09:31.119 --> 00:09:35.640
The third type or the third source of context are examples.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:40.760
So sometimes the stuff in either things that are online, right?

00:09:40.760 --> 00:09:45.200
We just saw, for example, documentations, academic papers,

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:47.799
Stack Overflow, pages, GitHub issues,

00:09:47.799 --> 00:09:50.559
those things may be not very specific,

00:09:50.559 --> 00:09:53.599
not very specific to what you want to do.

00:09:53.599 --> 00:09:58.039
In this case, you can provide to the point, short and concise examples.

00:09:58.039 --> 00:10:01.280
So in this case, a very simple example is the conversion

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:04.559
between HTML tag and Shiny UI.

00:10:04.559 --> 00:10:07.719
This is exactly all that Copilot needs to do

00:10:07.719 --> 00:10:11.159
in order to complete the task here.

00:10:11.159 --> 00:10:14.960
Now, a tale of caution here, not all context helps.

00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:19.840
There are some types of context that can actually stop Copilot

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:23.039
or large language models from working.

00:10:23.039 --> 00:10:25.760
And as we can see here, I'm already a hundred lines

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:30.559
into letting Copilot providing correct working R code

00:10:30.559 --> 00:10:35.239
that to reproduce the HTML file, but it stopped line 101,

00:10:35.239 --> 00:10:38.000
mail two, and then no completions available.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:40.559
How come tags A is hyperlink, right?

00:10:40.559 --> 00:10:42.159
Hyperlink is very common.

00:10:42.159 --> 00:10:46.919
It shouldn't have any difficulty creating the right hyperlink using R.

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:52.679
Why? Well, if you have some experience using Copilot for data analytics,

00:10:52.679 --> 00:10:56.280
you can probably spot the red flag, which is mail two,

00:10:56.280 --> 00:10:59.359
because email is a piece of personal information.

00:10:59.359 --> 00:11:03.880
Similar things that can cause problems for Copilot to let it stop

00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:08.320
include your address, IP address, things that can cause bias,

00:11:08.320 --> 00:11:11.840
for example, your gender identity, immigration status.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:15.880
Those things can trigger the internal safety measures,

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:18.960
anti-bias measures of the large language models

00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:21.000
and make it stop working.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:25.239
Now, this means it's very important for you to know your context, number one.

00:11:25.239 --> 00:11:27.520
And if you're not sure, you ask Copilot.

00:11:27.520 --> 00:11:31.599
So in this case, I use the question type of prompt,

00:11:31.599 --> 00:11:33.000
tell Copilot answer in English.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.640
I also lead in with the word answer,

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:39.960
and Copilot will tell me where in the context

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:43.520
I can have this concern about privacy or bias.

00:11:43.520 --> 00:11:47.960
And it's very important for us whenever we use large language models

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:51.880
to be aware and mitigate those risks.

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:56.039
Okay, the last part of this basic workflow is iteration.

00:11:56.039 --> 00:12:00.960
So iteration is the continuous improvement of your prompt

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:05.320
or your context in order to improve the quality of your response.

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:08.520
So the use of Copilot is not a one-time thing.

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:12.640
You gradually improve your prompt and your response.

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:16.799
Now, to demonstrate, so I have three ideas to share with you

00:12:16.799 --> 00:12:17.799
when it comes to iteration.

00:12:17.799 --> 00:12:22.000
Number one, you do documentation first to enrich your context,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
the important part of iteration.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:27.960
Number two, you iterate from static data to dynamic data.

00:12:27.960 --> 00:12:30.919
And number three, you iterate from something that's task

00:12:30.919 --> 00:12:34.719
or project-specific to something that can be used

00:12:34.719 --> 00:12:38.239
across the board as an internal prompt dictionary.

00:12:38.239 --> 00:12:42.159
To demonstrate these points, I will use Copilot to create tests

00:12:42.159 --> 00:12:44.039
for this very simple Shiny app.

00:12:44.039 --> 00:12:47.679
The Shiny app we saw of stock prices is very simple,

00:12:47.679 --> 00:12:50.479
and there are three types of tests I want to show,

00:12:50.479 --> 00:12:52.520
unit, browser, and server.

00:12:52.520 --> 00:12:56.400
And the first test is a unit test, a very simple test.

00:12:57.359 --> 00:13:00.559
I'm pretty sure 90% of you know what's a unit test.

00:13:00.559 --> 00:13:03.919
It looks at the input and the output of the function.

00:13:03.919 --> 00:13:08.960
Now, I want to create a unit test for this very simple function

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:12.479
to transform data from wide form to long form.

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:13.679
Now, what do I do?

00:13:13.679 --> 00:13:17.159
I actually do not ask for unit test first.

00:13:17.159 --> 00:13:20.640
Instead, I ask Copilot to create documentation.

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:21.479
Why?

00:13:21.479 --> 00:13:24.799
Because number one, Copilot is typically very good

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:27.960
at generating documentations for functions

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:31.960
or specifically for Shiny modules as well.

00:13:31.960 --> 00:13:34.400
And number two, when we have the documentation,

00:13:34.400 --> 00:13:36.640
we put the documentation up there, right?

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:39.880
It goes back, it becomes part of the context,

00:13:39.880 --> 00:13:42.239
and it makes the next step,

00:13:42.239 --> 00:13:46.000
which is creating the unit test, more effective.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.840
And in this case, we can see Copilot is great

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:52.359
at creating a proper unit test for this function.

00:13:53.359 --> 00:13:58.039
Now, the next type of test I want to share is browser test.

00:13:58.039 --> 00:13:59.520
So what's a browser test?

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:02.880
A browser test, if you use Shiny in your work,

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:04.200
you probably do it.

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:06.799
It uses the Shiny Test2 package.

00:14:06.799 --> 00:14:10.400
It basically creates a virtual server

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:12.840
and a virtual browser,

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:15.320
and take a snapshot of your app,

00:14:15.320 --> 00:14:17.599
either literally as an image

00:14:17.599 --> 00:14:20.799
or take a snapshot of the HTML output.

00:14:20.799 --> 00:14:24.559
So in this case, I want to have a browser test

00:14:24.559 --> 00:14:26.919
of the HTML table in the middle.

00:14:26.919 --> 00:14:29.039
It's a big table, it has a lot of numbers.

00:14:29.039 --> 00:14:31.880
A lot of numbers are stock prices.

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:33.359
Now, what's the problem here?

00:14:33.359 --> 00:14:35.880
It's actually a common issue

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:38.760
when we use the Shiny Test2 package.

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:41.520
That is, the data is not static.

00:14:41.520 --> 00:14:42.880
Data is dynamic.

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:45.239
The next time we run the test, right,

00:14:45.239 --> 00:14:49.320
what happens is stock prices have changed,

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:50.760
but we assume it doesn't change.

00:14:51.280 --> 00:14:52.719
So the test will fail.

00:14:53.599 --> 00:14:55.559
In this case, I go into the place

00:14:55.559 --> 00:14:57.760
where the comparison is made,

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:00.479
and I ask Copilot to create this function,

00:15:00.479 --> 00:15:02.320
transform HTML.

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:05.479
It transforms the HTML output,

00:15:05.479 --> 00:15:07.719
extract the part that is predictable,

00:15:07.719 --> 00:15:11.239
the number of rows, number of columns, row headers,

00:15:11.239 --> 00:15:14.440
but it discards the part that will change over time,

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:15.719
the data, of course.

00:15:15.719 --> 00:15:19.039
And this way, the next time I run the browser test,

00:15:19.039 --> 00:15:20.640
it will not fail.

00:15:21.520 --> 00:15:24.200
This is a very powerful solution to many of the problems

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:25.640
when we use Shiny Test2.

00:15:26.719 --> 00:15:29.440
Okay, the third test, type of test, is server test.

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:33.239
A lightweight test looks at the input, the output,

00:15:33.239 --> 00:15:35.919
and the reactive values, reactive expressions,

00:15:35.919 --> 00:15:38.080
and how they interact with each other.

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:41.479
So the first situation, I tell Shiny what to do.

00:15:41.479 --> 00:15:43.359
Without any more information,

00:15:43.359 --> 00:15:47.760
sorry, Copilot is not creating any test at all.

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:49.919
It's not effective at all.

00:15:49.960 --> 00:15:52.599
And on the top of that, the second iteration,

00:15:52.599 --> 00:15:56.479
I added reference to knowledge on the internet.

00:15:56.479 --> 00:15:59.000
And with this iteration, we can see,

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.359
I had to use the correct functions,

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:04.880
but the expected function is outside the server,

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:07.159
so still a small problem there.

00:16:07.159 --> 00:16:10.400
And then on the top of that, the third iteration,

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:13.080
I added examples, a very short example.

00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:15.760
I copy and pasted it from the Mastering Shiny book,

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:19.760
but with this example, it's basically a very simple app.

00:16:20.479 --> 00:16:23.640
The server function and the server test as well.

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:26.640
And with this last iteration,

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:29.159
finally Copilot's able to use the correct functions,

00:16:29.159 --> 00:16:30.400
test that test server,

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:33.599
and also the actual test are also correct.

00:16:33.599 --> 00:16:37.719
Now, pay attention to this because all the context,

00:16:37.719 --> 00:16:41.880
all the prompt we have here are not specific to the task.

00:16:41.880 --> 00:16:44.960
They can be used elsewhere whenever we use,

00:16:44.960 --> 00:16:46.640
we want to create a server test.

00:16:46.679 --> 00:16:49.919
And the same principle goes to things like security

00:16:49.919 --> 00:16:52.840
and the compliance conventions of your organization,

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:54.840
how you do coding and documentation

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:56.840
and how you deploy your applications.

00:16:56.840 --> 00:16:59.440
All those things can be used elsewhere

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:02.280
and we collect them as part of prompt dictionary

00:17:02.280 --> 00:17:04.359
into our knowledge base.

